<!--
    ServiceNow Update Set record-definition for the `sys_hub_flow` row that
    declares the `x_casemgmt_validate_pending_transition` Flow Designer
    SUBFLOW (type=subflow) inside the scoped application `x_casemgmt`
    (Case Management).

    PURPOSE (AAP Section 0.5.5 verbatim):
        From          To           Required condition / behavior
        In Progress   Pending      None; sets pending_reason
                                   (Awaiting Info / Awaiting Third Party / Other)

    This subflow is the SIMPLEST of the FIVE shared transition-validation
    subflows under `servicenow-case-management-poc/flows/sub_flows/`. It is
    called by both parent state-machine flows whenever a case's `status`
    field changes to `Pending`:

      - ../general_inquiry_state_machine.xml
            (when a General Inquiry case enters the Pending sub-state)
      - ../complaint_state_machine.xml
            (when a Complaint case enters the Pending sub-state)

    UNLIKE the other four subflows in this folder, this subflow has:

      - NO required-condition gate. Per AAP Section 0.5.5 verbatim, the
        In Progress -> Pending transition has "None" required condition.
        The transition is ALWAYS permitted from In Progress (the inverse,
        Pending -> In Progress, is also unconditional - see
        ../../business_rules/x_casemgmt_clear_pending_reason_on_inprogress.xml
        which clears pending_reason on the reverse transition).

      - NO Throw Error step. There is no validation failure mode for this
        transition - the parent flow always proceeds to the Pending status
        once this subflow returns.

      - NO Script Include call. The other four subflows (validate_open,
        validate_inprogress, validate_resolved, validate_closed) call
        ../../script_includes/x_casemgmt_CaseTransitionValidator.xml for
        their precondition checks; this subflow has no precondition to
        check, so it does not invoke the validator.

      - NO role check. validate_closed_transition.xml verifies the caller
        has the x_casemgmt_case_manager role; this subflow imposes no role
        gate (any role with write access to the case can transition to
        Pending - the ACL matrix in AAP Section 0.5.6 governs WHICH users
        can update the case at all, but transitioning to Pending requires
        no additional role above and beyond standard write access).

    WHAT THIS SUBFLOW DOES:
        Stamps the `pending_reason` field on the parent case row with the
        Choice value supplied by the caller (or 'Other' if the caller did
        not supply one). That is its ENTIRE behavior. The parent flow
        handles status persistence; this subflow handles only the
        side-effect of recording WHY the case is now Pending.

    SEMANTIC SOURCE-SIDE REFERENCE (read-only, NOT byte-for-byte ported):

      - acm-plugins/acm-default-plugins/acm-case-file-plugin/src/main/
        java/com/armedia/acm/plugins/casefile/service/
        ChangeCaseFileStateService.java line 79-114 - the central
        ArkCase case state-machine service. Its changeCaseState(auth,
        caseId, newState, ipAddress) method:

            1) Loads the CaseFile by ID
            2) Returns early if status unchanged
            3) Sets the new status on the entity (line 95: retval.setStatus(newState))
            4) For "CLOSED" status, sets the close timestamp (lines 97-100)
            5) Saves the entity (line 102)
            6) Raises an event for downstream notification listeners
               (line 106: getCaseFileEventUtility().raiseEvent(...))

        That single method covered EVERY transition by string-matching
        the `newState` parameter. The ServiceNow target instead splits
        per-transition logic into FIVE dedicated subflows, one per
        transition target status, plus a small handful of Business
        Rules. The Pending-target slice of the original method was a
        no-op because ArkCase's String column had no Pending sub-state
        with a typed reason. The ServiceNow target ADDS the typed
        reason mechanism (the pending_reason Choice column declared in
        ../../dictionary/x_casemgmt_case_pending_reason.xml) and uses
        THIS subflow to populate it on the In Progress -> Pending edge.

      - acm-plugins/acm-default-plugins/acm-task-plugin/src/main/java/
        com/armedia/acm/plugins/task/model/AcmTask.java's
        `pendingStatus` String attribute is the closest semantic
        ancestor of the `pending_reason` field this subflow writes.
        AcmTask.pendingStatus was a free-form String describing the
        task's pending sub-state; the ServiceNow target generalizes
        the pattern (free-form -> closed Choice list of three values)
        and applies it at the case level rather than the task level.
        This subflow is the writer that PUTS the value on the case row.

      - The event-raising side-effect on line 106 of
        ChangeCaseFileStateService.java is INTENTIONALLY OMITTED here
        per the email-disabled constraint (AAP Section 0.7.2). ArkCase's
        raiseEvent() call would have triggered downstream notification
        listeners; the ServiceNow POC has no equivalent gs.eventQueue()
        call in this subflow because email is disabled on the PDI and
        no other in-scope listeners need the event.

    SUBFLOW INPUTS (Flow Designer declarative parameters):

      1. case_record  (Reference to x_casemgmt_case, MANDATORY)
            Passed in by the parent flow as $trigger.current. This is
            the case row whose pending_reason field will be stamped.
            The parent flow's OnUpdate trigger fires when status
            changes to 'Pending', and the trigger's $trigger.current
            is the just-updated case GlideRecord.

      2. pending_reason  (Choice, OPTIONAL, default 'Other')
            One of the three Choice values declared in
            ../../choices/sys_choice_case_pending_reason.xml:
              - 'Awaiting Info'
              - 'Awaiting Third Party'
              - 'Other'
            The parent flow may pass a value from a UI Action input
            field, a Flow Designer prompt step, or any computed source.
            If the parent flow does not pass a value, this subflow
            defaults to 'Other' to ensure the field is never left
            empty after a Pending transition (which would degrade the
            Manager View dashboard's analytics surface).

    SUBFLOW STEPS (ordered):

      Step 1: Default pending_reason if empty
            A Set Flow Variable step that ensures the pending_reason
            input is non-empty. If the caller passed 'Awaiting Info',
            'Awaiting Third Party', or 'Other', the value is preserved
            unchanged. If the caller passed null, undefined, empty
            string, or any other falsy value, the input is overwritten
            with 'Other'. This is the only normalization the subflow
            performs on its inputs; no character-level validation is
            done because the parent flow's Choice prompt restricts the
            input to the three legal values, and the dictionary entry's
            choice=3 enforcement at the platform level rejects any
            other value at insert/update time.

      Step 2: Set pending_reason on case
            An Update Record step that performs:
                case_record.pending_reason = pending_reason
            This is the subflow's sole side effect. The platform's
            standard Business Rule pipeline runs against the update
            (including the sibling
            ../../business_rules/x_casemgmt_clear_pending_reason_on_inprogress.xml
            which is a NO-OP for this transition because it only
            fires on the reverse Pending -> In Progress edge). The
            row is persisted at the end of the parent flow's
            transaction.

    OUTPUTS:
        None. The subflow is fire-and-forget from the parent flow's
        perspective. The parent flow does not need a return value
        because the side effect (pending_reason on the case row) is
        directly visible through the standard form refresh and the
        related lists.

    SCOPED-NAMESPACE CONSTRAINT (AAP Section 0.7.2):
        - <name>x_casemgmt_validate_pending_transition</name> uses the
          x_casemgmt scope prefix per the auto-assigned scoped-app
          namespace.
        - <sys_scope>x_casemgmt</sys_scope> binds THIS subflow record
          to the x_casemgmt scope.
        - <sys_package source="x_casemgmt">x_casemgmt</sys_package>
          binds THIS subflow record to the x_casemgmt application
          package.
        - The Flow Designer snapshot below references the
          x_casemgmt_case table by name (NOT sys_id), and references
          the pending_reason field by element name (NOT sys_id).
        Zero global-scope writes. Zero modifications to OOB tables
        (sys_user, sys_user_group, sys_user_role, core_company,
         task, incident, etc.).

    NO-HARDCODED-SYS_ID CONSTRAINT (AAP Section 0.7.2):
        - <sys_scope> resolves the scope record BY NAME (x_casemgmt)
        - <sys_package> resolves the application record BY NAME
          (x_casemgmt) via its `source` attribute
        - The subflow snapshot references the x_casemgmt_case table
          BY NAME ("table": "x_casemgmt_case") and field BY NAME
          ("pending_reason"); zero `sys_id` literal references
          appear anywhere in the snapshot or audit-field XML.
        - The <sys_id> element below is THIS record's own deterministic
          primary key (MD5 of "x_casemgmt_validate_pending_transition"),
          which is permitted because the AAP "no hardcoded sys_id" rule
          applies to REFERENCE FIELDS pointing at OTHER records, not
          to a record's own primary key. The deterministic derivation
          ensures idempotent re-import on a fresh PDI - re-importing
          the same Update Set produces the same sys_id, which collides
          on the existing record and updates it in place rather than
          creating a duplicate.

    EMAIL-DISABLED CONSTRAINT (AAP Section 0.7.2):
        The subflow MUST NOT call gs.eventQueue('...') for any email
        notification event since email is disabled on the PDI. This
        subflow contains zero gs.eventQueue() calls, zero Send Email
        actions, and zero notification trigger steps. It performs
        only the field-set side effect on the case row. This
        intentionally diverges from ArkCase ChangeCaseFileStateService
        line 106 raiseEvent() which would have triggered downstream
        notification listeners; the ServiceNow POC omits the
        equivalent call per the AAP minimal-change clause.

    NO PII (AAP Section 0.7.2):
        The description text, code comments, and snapshot inline
        labels contain zero real names, real email addresses, real
        phone numbers, real organizational identifiers, or any other
        personally identifiable information. The subflow operates
        exclusively on a case-row reference, a controlled-vocabulary
        Choice value, and a target field name.

    ACTIVE-PUBLISHED STATE (CRITICAL per agent prompt Phase 2.3):
        - <active>true</active>      - subflow is enabled, NOT Draft
        - <status>published</status> - subflow is published, NOT draft
        Both are required for the parent flows to be able to call
        this subflow at runtime. A Draft-state subflow is callable
        only from the Flow Designer canvas during testing; published
        is the production-ready state.

    TYPE=SUBFLOW (CRITICAL per agent prompt Phase 2.4):
        - <type>subflow</type>
        Subflows are reusable building blocks called by parent flows
        via the "Call a Subflow" action. A type=flow record cannot
        be called by another flow; the platform looks for type=subflow
        records when resolving a "Call a Subflow" reference. The
        parent flows in ../general_inquiry_state_machine.xml and
        ../complaint_state_machine.xml reference this subflow BY
        NAME (x_casemgmt_validate_pending_transition), and the
        platform's lookup at activation time resolves to THIS record
        because of the type=subflow setting.

    RUN_AS=CALLER (CRITICAL per agent prompt Phase 2.4):
        - <run_as>caller</run_as>
        The subflow inherits the run-as context of the calling parent
        flow. The parent flows use run_as=user_who_triggers, so when
        the parent calls this subflow, the subflow ALSO runs as the
        triggering user. This ensures the Update Record step's write
        is correctly attributed (sys_updated_by tracks the actual
        user who initiated the Pending transition, not the system
        account). It also ensures any future role-aware logic added
        to this subflow would evaluate against the correct user.

    UPDATE-SET LOAD ORDER (AAP Section 0.5.2):

        This sys_hub_flow record MUST be loaded AFTER:

          - ../../app/sys_app/x_casemgmt_case_management.xml
              (scoped application; <sys_package> reference resolution)
          - ../../app/sys_scope/x_casemgmt.xml
              (scope record; <sys_scope> reference resolution)
          - ../../tables/x_casemgmt_case.xml
              (parent table; the case_record input parameter is a
               Reference to this table, and the Update Record step
               targets this table)
          - ../../dictionary/x_casemgmt_case_pending_reason.xml
              (the field this subflow writes - must exist before the
               Update Record step can resolve the field name)
          - ../../dictionary/x_casemgmt_case_status.xml
              (the field whose change to 'Pending' triggers the
               parent flow's OnUpdate filter; must exist before the
               parent flow's trigger filter can resolve)
          - ../../choices/sys_choice_case_pending_reason.xml
              (the choice list that bounds the legal values of the
               pending_reason input parameter; must exist so the
               subflow's Choice input can resolve its allowed values)

        And BEFORE:

          - ../general_inquiry_state_machine.xml
              (parent flow that calls this subflow on the General
               Inquiry case-type's In Progress -> Pending edge)
          - ../complaint_state_machine.xml
              (parent flow that calls this subflow on the Complaint
               case-type's In Progress -> Pending edge)

    DETERMINISTIC SYS_ID:
        sys_id = MD5("x_casemgmt_validate_pending_transition")
               = 94063d7d535c4e841ad7deb0b45e8ba5
        32-character lowercase hex. The PDI accepts any valid 32-char
        hex sys_id; deriving from the record name guarantees idempotent
        re-import on a fresh PDI: re-importing the same Update Set
        produces the same sys_id, which collides on the existing
        record and updates it in place rather than creating a duplicate.
        This is the same convention used by every other deterministically-
        keyed record in this Update Set (e.g.,
        ../../business_rules/x_casemgmt_set_closed_date.xml whose
        sys_id is f6d63b3856121cac9b69215b2c46f64c).

    VALIDATION GATE MAPPING (AAP Section 0.7.3):

        - Gate 2 (Workflow): "All state transitions enforced for both
          case types - Invalid transitions return blocking error;
          task-closure check blocks Resolved transition." This subflow
          contributes to Gate 2 by ENSURING the In Progress -> Pending
          transition is permitted and properly stamps the
          pending_reason field. Although this transition has no
          validation gate per AAP Section 0.5.5, it must execute
          successfully and write the reason; otherwise Gate 2
          inspection of the Pending state would reveal an empty
          pending_reason field (which is a Gate 2 regression). The
          gate is verified by:
              1) Creating a case with status=In Progress and
                 assigned_agent populated.
              2) Setting status=Pending.
              3) The parent flow fires and dispatches to this subflow.
              4) The subflow sets pending_reason='Other' (or the value
                 supplied by the parent flow).
              5) The form displays the pending_reason value alongside
                 the new status.

        - Gate 6 (Dashboards): "Both dashboards render with synthetic
          data - All widgets display data; no broken report references."
          This subflow indirectly supports Gate 6 by populating
          pending_reason for any Pending case. Although no current
          dashboard widget groups by pending_reason, a future Manager
          View enhancement (e.g., a donut showing the breakdown of
          Awaiting Info vs Awaiting Third Party vs Other) would rely
          on this subflow having populated the column for every
          Pending row.

        - Gate 7 (Update Set): "Scoped app exported - Update Set loads
          without errors on a fresh PDI instance." The deterministic
          sys_id, reference-by-name pattern, and well-formed XML
          structure ensure this record re-imports cleanly with zero
          preview errors. The CDATA-wrapped JSON snapshot is the only
          element that contains characters requiring CDATA escaping
          (curly braces, quotes within JSON), and the CDATA section
          is properly opened and closed.

    FUTURE EXTENSIBILITY:
        If a future enhancement needs to record the Pending start
        time (e.g., a derived "time-spent-Pending" metric for
        process-improvement analysis), enrich this subflow rather
        than the parent flows. The parent flows should remain thin
        dispatchers; per-transition concerns belong here. Likewise,
        if email is later re-enabled on the PDI and a "Case is now
        Pending - awaiting [reason]" email is desired, add a Send
        Email step to THIS subflow rather than to the parent flows.
        Adding parameters to this subflow does not break the parent
        flows because Flow Designer's "Call a Subflow" action passes
        only the inputs the parent supplies; new optional inputs
        with defaults are backward-compatible.
-->
